20:50.549 --> 20:52.284 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to Trump's chances.

20:52.318 --> 20:55.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Your first election,
presidential election
was what year?

20:55.955 --> 20:57.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN STARK, Ohio: 1984.

20:57.123 --> 20:58.090 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: You voted for?

20:58.124 --> 20:59.558 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN STARK: For Reagan.

20:59.592 --> 21:03.028 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And which party's
candidate have
you voted for ever since?

21:03.062 --> 21:04.463 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN STARK: The Republicans.

21:04.497 --> 21:05.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Until now?

21:05.998 --> 21:09.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN STARK: Yes, I think this
will be the
first time not to, honestly.

21:09.101 --> 21:13.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Was that a difficult
decision for
you, as someone who has voted
for the Republican

21:13.038 --> 21:15.474 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
candidate every time since 1984?

21:15.508 --> 21:16.642 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
JOHN STARK: No.

21:16.675 --> 21:19.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I first saw Trump, I knew I
couldn't
vote for him.

21:19.411 --> 21:20.746 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

21:20.779 --> 21:23.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Nothing Trump has
said or done
since has swayed him.

21:23.315 --> 21:27.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN STARK: The Republican Party
to me is
a party of small government, low
regulations,

21:27.953 --> 21:29.388 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
low taxes.

21:29.421 --> 21:32.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And here we're not really sure
what he stands
for, except himself.

21:32.591 --> 21:34.627 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He likes to talk about himself a
lot.

21:34.660 --> 21:39.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Trump's economic
message doesn't
resonate with voters in this
prosperous county

21:39.198 --> 21:40.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like Stark.

21:40.399 --> 21:42.368 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He says business is good.

21:42.401 --> 21:47.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And his son got a job as an
audio engineer
a within a week of graduating
college.

21:47.973 --> 21:50.409 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Voting for Clinton was never an
option.

21:50.442 --> 21:51.877 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
His candidate?

21:51.911 --> 21:53.913 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Libertarian Gary Johnson.

21:53.946 --> 21:57.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you worry that voting for
Johnson could
help Clinton?

21:57.750 --> 22:00.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN STARK: I guess I don't
care.

22:00.352 --> 22:02.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, I got -- you got to
have principles,
right?

22:02.988 --> 22:08.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But it's not as if
Clinton's having
an easy ride here.

22:08.894 --> 22:15.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Cathy Okunlola was an
enthusiastic Barack
Obama supporter in 2008 and
2012.

22:15.267 --> 22:19.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
This time, she's backing
Clinton, but without
that same excitement.

22:19.205 --> 22:23.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CATHY OKUNLOLA, Clinton
Supporter: She's not
going to get up and have those
huge inspiring

22:23.909 --> 22:25.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rallies that Obama did, you
know?

22:25.811 --> 22:30.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not like a big party when
you walk in
the room for Hillary, but she
gets the job

22:30.482 --> 22:31.450 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
done.

22:31.483 --> 22:33.752 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she really wants to help
people, I think.

22:33.786 --> 22:35.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Like, she's doing it for the
right reasons,
I think.

22:35.988 --> 22:40.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: A stay-at-home mother
of two young
daughters, Okunlola said her
main goal on

22:40.826 --> 22:42.628 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Election Day is to beat Trump.

22:42.661 --> 22:44.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CATHY OKUNLOLA: I really dislike
Trump.

22:44.964 --> 22:49.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I never really believed he would
be the nominee,
but, hey, here we are.

22:49.168 --> 22:51.070 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, yes, so I'm voting for
Hillary.

22:51.103 --> 22:54.840 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: She struggled to put
her feelings
about Clinton into words.

22:54.873 --> 22:59.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CATHY OKUNLOLA: There's that kid
in your class
that just plugs away at
everything, you know?

22:59.411 --> 23:05.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not exactly the popular
kid, and they're
not exactly super talented at
music or anything,

23:05.451 --> 23:10.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but they just -- they study
hard, and they
show up, and they're always the
talk of the

23:10.055 --> 23:11.490 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
class.

23:11.523 --> 23:14.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama would have been the prom
king and everybody
would've loved him.

23:14.727 --> 23:18.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And everybody went to school
with somebody
like that, you know, that
everybody wanted

23:18.264 --> 23:20.032 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to be around.

23:20.065 --> 23:23.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she's not that person, but
she is somebody
where, if you were in trouble,
that's who

23:23.269 --> 23:25.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you wanted, you know?

23:25.204 --> 23:31.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Voters like Stark and
Okunlola
could well decide who wins Ohio
and perhaps,

23:31.243 --> 23:32.344 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the presidency.

23:32.378 --> 23:34.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Analyst Kyle Kondik:

23:34.513 --> 23:39.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KYLE KONDIK: I would suspect the
margin between
Trump and Clinton in Delaware
County will

23:39.051 --> 23:44.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be smaller than the typical
margin between
a Republican and Democrat in
this county,

23:44.189 --> 23:48.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that could be very helpful
to Clinton,
but Trump may have opportunities
to make that

23:48.661 --> 23:52.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up in some more traditionally
Democratic places
that might be a little bit more
Republican

23:52.865 --> 23:54.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this time.

23:54.767 --> 24:00.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: As voters face very
unpopular choices
and try to pick a winner in the
presidential

24:00.339 --> 24:01.707 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
horse race.

24:01.740 --> 24:05.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm John
Yang in Delaware
County, Ohio.

24:05.978 --> 24:11.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Tomorrow, John
crosses the state
to report from a traditional
Democratic stronghold

24:11.817 --> 24:14.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where Donald Trump is hoping to
make inroads.

24:14.053 --> 24:19.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But first: Big
companies today
are not creating nearly as many
middle-income

24:19.925 --> 24:25.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
jobs as they once did, and
that's been one
of the concerns in this
campaign.

24:25.531 --> 24:30.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
Solman went to
Detroit, where ideas for
spurring a new era

24:30.869 --> 24:33.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of local manufacturing are
taking shape.

24:33.839 --> 24:36.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series,
Making Sense.

24:36.875 --> 24:43.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: A must-see stop on
the grand
tour of decaying Detroit, the
plant that,

24:43.282 --> 24:46.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for decades, clanked out auto
chassis for
GM.

24:46.585 --> 24:50.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY DAVIS, University of
Michigan: General
Motors at its height had 900,000
employees,

24:50.923 --> 24:52.358 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
career ladders galore.

24:52.391 --> 24:56.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were providing a lot of
benefits, creating
good middle-class jobs.

24:56.128 --> 24:59.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GM today has about 220,000
employees around
the world.

24:59.965 --> 25:02.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's about as many as it had in
1928.

25:02.301 --> 25:09.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But sociologist
Jerry Davis says
the GMs of yesteryear, though
models of productivity

25:09.274 --> 25:12.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and even of economic equality,
are history.

25:12.077 --> 25:15.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY DAVIS: What happened to
General Motors
didn't just happen to General
Motors.

25:15.781 --> 25:20.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are about half as many
public corporations
today as they were 20 years ago.

25:20.152 --> 25:25.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, instead of
General Motors,
U.S. Steel, Eastman Kodak, and I
could go

25:25.424 --> 25:26.925 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on and on, what have we got?

25:26.959 --> 25:30.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JERRY DAVIS: The big
corporations today don't
really have that many employees.

25:30.295 --> 25:31.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're not providing career
ladders.

25:32.030 --> 25:34.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They're not creating
middle-class jobs.

25:34.266 --> 25:39.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Blockbuster had 80,000 employees
and 9,000
stores across the country.

25:39.204 --> 25:42.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Netflix does the same thing with
fewer than
4,000 people.

25:42.741 --> 25:46.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If anybody tells you they work
at Facebook,
probably they mean they are a
contractor,

25:46.945 --> 25:50.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because only about 12,000 people
actually
work at Facebook.

25:50.382 --> 25:54.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are worth $300 billion, but
very few
people actually work there.

25:54.787 --> 26:00.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In a new book,
Davis calls it
the vanishing American
corporation and poses

26:00.292 --> 26:04.897 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a pivotal question: What will
rise from the
wreckage?

26:04.930 --> 26:08.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mega-firms that hire relatively
few workers?

26:08.634 --> 26:10.836 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Made-anywhere product peddlers
like Nike?

26:10.869 --> 26:14.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY DAVIS: They're the biggest
sneaker and
sporting goods company in the
world, but they

26:14.973 --> 26:18.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't actually make most of the
stuff with
their name brand on it.

26:18.410 --> 26:22.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They design it, they market it
from Oregon,
but the production is done by
contractors

26:22.614 --> 26:23.882 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
all around the world.

26:23.916 --> 26:25.617 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that model is spread widely.

26:25.651 --> 26:28.153 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not just sneakers, it's not
just garments.

26:28.187 --> 26:32.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Electronics, pharmaceuticals,
pet food, you
name the product, and you can
find somebody

26:32.624 --> 26:35.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to manufacture it and put your
name on it.

26:35.093 --> 26:40.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Nikefication, Davis
has dubbed
it, exemplified by another
multinational with

26:40.199 --> 26:42.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a Detroit foothold, Ikea.

26:42.134 --> 26:46.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY DAVIS: The Ikea model is
you manufacture
it somewhere, you ship it out
around the world,

26:46.905 --> 26:48.674 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
flat pack.

26:48.707 --> 26:51.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So this model might be a very
good model for
customers because it's very
inexpensive.

26:51.877 --> 26:54.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not the world's best
furniture, but you
can live with it.

26:54.913 --> 27:00.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And you do have to
assemble it
yourself or hire someone to do
it for you.

27:00.385 --> 27:04.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Indeed, these days, a world of
temps is only
a moment away.

27:04.890 --> 27:09.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY DAVIS: A business like
Upwork allows
you to find contractors to do
programming

27:09.495 --> 27:12.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and other tasks available around
the world.

27:12.197 --> 27:13.398 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Czech Republic.

27:13.432 --> 27:17.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Czech Republic,
U.S., Croatia,
Philippines.

27:17.603 --> 27:22.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the technology that allows
for such wonders,
and the wage exploitation of a
global race

27:22.841 --> 27:28.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the bottom, also suggests a
more appealing
future for work in America.

27:28.080 --> 27:32.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JERRY DAVIS: You can go to this
Web site and
see these great designs for
beds, chairs,

27:32.584 --> 27:35.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tables and so on, the kind of
thing that you
might buy at Ikea.

27:35.454 --> 27:39.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But these are designs that you
can download
and create locally.

27:39.224 --> 27:44.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Instead of
assembling Ikea furniture
themselves, that is, why can't
Americans also

27:44.730 --> 27:46.932 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
make it to their own
specifications?

27:46.965 --> 27:53.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JERRY DAVIS: So, this is
basically an Ikea-like
chair that's made out of metal,
but you could

27:53.705 --> 27:56.208 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
make it out of plastic or wood.

27:56.241 --> 27:58.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: These are just
prototypes or
models.

27:58.277 --> 27:59.378 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JERRY DAVIS: Yes.

27:59.411 --> 28:01.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are the designs online
shrunk to a tiny
version.

28:01.980 --> 28:04.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you could make a full-sized
version of
this, this afternoon.

28:04.616 --> 28:09.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So Davis took us to
TechShop
Detroit, where Vasile Vincent
(ph) was using

28:09.621 --> 28:15.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a computer-controlled cutting
machine to carve
a table leg based on an online
design.

28:15.527 --> 28:22.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For a monthly fee, members of
TechShop, a
nationwide chain, access all
manner of gadgetry.

28:22.734 --> 28:24.770 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Faith Olsen (ph) was working the
water jet
cutter.

28:24.803 --> 28:26.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FAITH OLSEN, TechShop Detroit:
It's using
sand.

28:27.005 --> 28:28.240 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's using water pressure.

28:28.273 --> 28:30.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's basically using erosion to
cut through.

28:30.475 --> 28:33.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have got eighth-inch aluminum
on there
right now.

28:33.312 --> 28:34.279 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Wow.

28:34.313 --> 28:36.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So that's cutting through
aluminum now.

28:36.148 --> 28:37.115 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
FAITH OLSEN: Yes.

28:37.149 --> 28:38.951 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's just cutting right through
it.

28:38.984 --> 28:43.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: TechShop is for
polished pros
and rank amateurs alike.

28:43.221 --> 28:45.891 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The manager of this Detroit site
is Will Brick.

28:45.924 --> 28:46.892 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So, who is this?

28:46.925 --> 28:47.893 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
The Red Baron?

28:47.926 --> 28:49.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILL BRICK, TechShop: Yes,
right.

28:49.061 --> 28:50.462 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I like to imagine that's me in
the cockpit
there.

28:50.495 --> 28:53.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Brick cooked up
this model airplane
for a summer camp.

28:53.298 --> 28:57.002 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILL BRICK: One of the things we
taught kids
to do was to build an airframe
and then add

28:57.035 --> 29:00.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a radio control mechanism to
actually be able
to remotely pilot it.

29:00.572 --> 29:05.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, future makers
learn how to
do it themselves, while
entrepreneurs hatch

29:05.444 --> 29:07.746 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the products of tomorrow.

29:07.779 --> 29:10.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The Rope Runner was the
brainchild of Kevin
Bingham.

29:10.415 --> 29:13.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILL BRICK: He came up with this
thing that
allows you to scale a tree, go
up and down

29:13.986 --> 29:17.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
without changing kit, and be as
nimble as
like a spider monkey, right?

29:17.155 --> 29:22.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He came into TechShop, drew up
some prototypes,
made some wooden mockups, and
cut out the

29:22.160 --> 29:27.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
finished aluminum pieces,
assembled all that,
and then engraved his logo and
the phrase

29:27.232 --> 29:31.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Made in Detroit," which I love,
into the
powder coating on the sides of
the apparatus.

29:31.503 --> 29:36.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: What Davis sees
budding in Detroit
is an alternative to a world run
by Nike and

29:36.975 --> 29:43.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ikea, manufacturing brought back
to America,
